[{'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Greetings from Constantinople. Let us speak plainly: we both have interests that need not conflict in 1901. I propose a simple arrangement - Turkey moves F ANK to BLA and A CON to BUL, while Russia focuses north and west. I have no designs on SEV this year if you keep F SEV away from BLA and ARM. A collision between us only benefits Austria and Italy. Confirm you will not contest BLA or move into ARM, and we can both expand profitably this year.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, I propose a friendly understanding for 1901. Turkey intends to move into BUL and secure the Balkans to our south. We have no interest in SER or RUM this year if you are moving there - those are yours to take. In return, I ask that you keep your fleet in TRI and not move into GRE or the Aegean. A Turkish-Austrian understanding in the Balkans benefits us both against Russian expansion southward. What are your intentions this year?'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, Turkey greets you. We are natural partners in the early game - your fleet in NAP and mine in ANK need not clash. I am moving to secure BUL and the Black Sea this year. I have no interest in the Ionian or Aegean if you are moving west toward France. Let us agree to keep our fleets out of each other's way in 1901 and focus on our respective expansions. A Turkish-Italian understanding could prove very valuable as the game develops."}]
