[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England, we are in agreement. My fleet moves to Denmark, my army to Holland - you take Norway. This is clean and efficient. On France: I note their army is moving to Burgundy this spring, which threatens both of us. I intend to push through Burgundy toward Paris in the coming seasons. If you pressure France from the Channel and Brest, we can squeeze them from both sides. I will not move against your home territories - Kiel and the North Sea can remain a boundary between us. Let us formalize this: DEN and HOL to Germany, NWY to England, and we coordinate against France in 1902.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, your terms are acceptable in principle, but I must be direct: Sweden is a German interest as well as a Russian one. I propose Denmark and Sweden for Germany, Norway for Russia - this keeps our fleets separated and avoids friction. I am moving F KIE to Denmark this spring. I have no designs on Warsaw or your eastern territories - Galicia and Rumania are yours to contest. Let us agree: no German units east of Silesia, no Russian units west of Warsaw, and we both profit while the western powers exhaust themselves.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, I am pleased we understand each other. My moves this spring: F KIE to Denmark, A MUN to Burgundy, A BER to Silesia - positioning for western expansion while securing my eastern flank. I ask specifically that you move A VIE to Galicia or Tyrolia rather than Bohemia - Bohemia must remain a German buffer. In return, I will support your moves against Serbia and Rumania. Italy is your natural enemy in the south; I will not interfere there. A strong Austro-German axis from the Rhine to the Danube is the foundation of continental order.'}]
