ITA
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, I hear your concern about A TYR - rest assured, my army is positioned to watch Germany and potentially support a move toward Munich, not to threaten Vienna or Trieste. I'm taking Tunis this fall and have no Austrian targets in 1901. However, I want to be direct: if you continue expanding aggressively in the Balkans without sharing gains, I'll need to reconsider our arrangement in 1902. For now, A TYR stays put or moves toward MUN - your home centers are safe from me this year."}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Turkey, confirmed - Greece is yours this fall, I have no fleet moving to GRE or AEG. F ION moves to TUN, A APU supports. Our arrangement holds. Looking ahead to 1902, I propose we coordinate against Austria together - they're getting strong in the Balkans and that threatens us both. You push from BUL/GRE toward Serbia and Bulgaria, I pressure Trieste from the Adriatic. A divided Balkans benefits us both far more than letting Austria consolidate. Let's discuss specifics next spring."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, your read on Austria is correct - they've taken Serbia and Galicia in one move, which is alarming. I'm keeping A TYR positioned to pressure them if needed. My fall moves are F ION-TUN and A APU supports, securing Tunis. In 1902 I intend to open a second front against Austria via the Adriatic. If you can keep Germany occupied in the west, we can squeeze Austria from both sides and divide their centers. Are you willing to coordinate a joint pressure campaign against Austria starting in 1902?"}]
--------------
ENG
[{'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, I've received your message and I must be direct: I cannot stand aside from BEL this fall. I have F ENG positioned and intend to move there - this was always my plan and I communicated it clearly. If you move A BUR to BEL we will bounce and neither of us gains. I strongly urge you to redirect A BUR elsewhere - perhaps hold or move toward GER - and let me take BEL cleanly. You secure POR with F MAO, I take NOR and BEL, and we both build. A bounce in BEL helps only Germany. Make the smart choice."}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "Germany, I've confirmed my intentions: F NTH to NOR, F ENG to BEL. I will NOT support your HOL move this fall as I need both fleets for my own expansion, but I have no objection to you taking HOL - just move A KIE there directly. France is apparently moving A BUR to BEL which would bounce me - if you can move A RUH to BEL instead to support my entry, or simply hold RUH to threaten BUR, that would be mutually beneficial. In 1902 I am very open to coordinating pressure on France from the west while you push from the east."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, final word before orders: I am taking Norway this fall with F NTH. Sweden and St. Petersburg are yours to develop - I will not contest them. I propose we formalize a northern non-aggression understanding: Scandinavia divided between us with Norway as English and Sweden as Russian sphere. This frees us both to focus on our real strategic interests elsewhere. I look forward to a productive relationship.'}]
--------------
RUS
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, I must be blunt: F RUM will not yield that center. I took it fair and square this spring and I intend to keep it. Your A GAL moving to RUM will simply bounce - we both waste a move and Turkey grows stronger. Here is my genuine offer: I will support Austrian expansion into the Balkans against Turkey. If you move A SER toward GRE or pressure BUL, I will coordinate from RUM. But if you attack RUM, I will treat it as a declaration of war and coordinate with Turkey to dismember Austria. The choice is yours - profitable cooperation or mutual destruction.'}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Excellent - our coordination continues to work perfectly. I confirm: F RUM holds and secures that center. Austria is threatening to move A GAL to RUM this fall - I need your F BLA to support F RUM to hold against any attack. In return, I fully support A BUL moving to GRE to secure that center for you. This is a concrete exchange: your fleet supports my position, I endorse your Greek expansion. Austria is the threat to both of us - let us keep them contained together. Confirm you will order F BLA S F RUM.'}, {'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England, I accept your claim on Norway this fall - F NTH to NOR is yours uncontested. In return, I expect you to respect Sweden and Finland as my natural sphere going forward. My F STP/SC will move to BOT this fall to position for Sweden in 1902. We have a clean division: you take Norway, I take Sweden. This keeps Scandinavia stable between us and lets us both focus on more pressing threats. Confirm this arrangement and we have a durable northern understanding.'}]
--------------
AUT
[{'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, I've heard your proposal and I want to find a workable arrangement. Here is my final position: I am moving A GAL to RUM this fall. If F RUM holds or retreats, we avoid a bounce and I take the center peacefully. If you move F RUM elsewhere, I will take RUM and in return I commit to keeping A GAL out of UKR and WAR for all of 1902, and I will actively support Russian interests against Turkey in the Black Sea. A bounce helps neither of us - Turkey grows while we stall. Make the pragmatic choice: let RUM go this year, and we build a durable partnership against the real threats."}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Turkey, I want to be transparent with you: I am moving F ALB to GRE this fall and A SER holds to secure Serbia. I am NOT moving on BUL - that is yours as agreed. On RUM, I am pushing A GAL there to contest Russia's F RUM. I need you to understand this is about blocking Russian expansion, not threatening your sphere. If Russia is weakened in RUM, it benefits both of us. Please move A BUL to support GRE or hold - do not move A BUL to RUM, as that would create a three-way mess. Let's each take our centers cleanly this fall."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, glad to hear F ION moves to TUN - that's clean and keeps our arrangement intact. I confirm A TYR holding is acceptable for now, but I'd ask you to move it toward MUN or VEN in 1902 rather than toward TRI or VIE. My fall moves: A GAL to RUM, F ALB to GRE, A SER holds. I'm expanding east and south, not toward you. Let's discuss 1902 coordination - a joint approach to containing Russia and Germany could benefit us both enormously."}]
--------------
TUR
[{'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, confirmed - my orders this Fall: A BUL to GRE (securing that center), F BLA holds or supports your F RUM to maintain position, A CON moves to SMY to free up CON for a build. I will NOT move against RUM or SEV - those are yours. Austria's F ALB is moving toward GRE and their A SER threatens RUM - they are the immediate danger. I strongly suggest your F RUM holds RUM firmly; if Austria tries to take it, I will support you diplomatically and position forces to pressure them from the south. Let us both build this winter and coordinate a joint squeeze on Austria in 1902."}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, I must be direct: F ALB moving to GRE is unacceptable - Greece is my sphere as we agreed, and I am moving A BUL there this Fall. If you send F ALB to GRE, we will clash and both lose. Instead, I urge you to move F ALB to hold or support A SER - Russia's F RUM is sitting on a center you want, and that is where your energy should go. Keep our agreement: you take the northern Balkans, I take the south. Do not contest GRE or you make an enemy of Turkey at the worst possible time."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, confirmed - GRE is mine this Fall, Tunis is yours. My A BUL moves to GRE, your F ION moves to TUN. We are in complete agreement. Austria is trying to send F ALB to GRE to block me - if they succeed, it destabilizes the entire southern theater and threatens both of us. I am proceeding with A BUL to GRE regardless. Long-term, I propose we maintain this division: I dominate the eastern Mediterranean and Balkans, you dominate the western Mediterranean and Italy. A formal non-aggression through 1903 would serve us both well.'}]
