FRA
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England — MUN bounced in Fall, so we both ended 1901 at 5 centers with no builds. The situation is clean: you hold BEL and NWY, I hold SPA and POR. This spring I intend A BUR to MUN and A SPA to GAS, pressing Germany hard from the west. I need you to hold BEL firm and consider moving F BEL to support a push on HOL if Germany reacts aggressively. Germany at 5 centers with DEN, HOL, and a Rhine army is the continental threat — we should squeeze them now before they consolidate. What are your intentions this spring?'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy — Austria holds SER, WAR, BUD, VIE — four centers and growing. Your A TRI is well-placed. I strongly encourage you to press into the Adriatic and keep Austria pinned in the Balkans this spring. If Austria turns west or north unchecked, it becomes everyone's problem. I have no designs on your sphere — Iberia and the Rhine are my focus. A coordinated Franco-Italian pressure on Austria's flanks in 1902 serves us both. What are you planning for TRI and the Adriatic?"}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': 'Germany — the MUN bounce last fall was an accident of timing, not a declaration of war. I am willing to discuss a boundary: France stays out of MUN if Germany stays out of BEL and BUR. You have HOL and DEN secured — that is a strong northern position. England is your real naval problem, not France. I can offer A BUR as a buffer rather than a threat if we reach an understanding. But I need a response this round — silence will be read as hostility and I will act accordingly.'}]
INFO:main:Negotiation sub-round 2/2
