AUT
[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Turkey, I accept your proposal. This turn: F GRE moves to ION, vacating Greece for you. A SER moves to BUD to retake my home center from Italy. A BUD supports A SER into BUD. I need one thing from you: if F RUM can support A SER into BUL next turn, or simply hold and not threaten SER, that gives me the stability to focus entirely on Italy. Russia in RUM is indeed a shared problem - once I recover BUD, I am open to coordinating against Russia from the north while you press from the south. Let us execute this cleanly: I vacate GRE, you take it, we both gain. Confirm you will not move on SER this turn.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, final offer: I am moving A SER to BUD this turn. If you hold A VIE in place and do not support A BUD against my move, I retake BUD and we stabilize at VIE/TRI for you, BUD/SER/GRE for me. If you fight me for BUD, you waste moves while France sits at 6 centers and Russia at 5 - both of whom will eventually turn on you. I am not your real problem. I am offering you a stable western Balkan border so you can focus north and west. The alternative is a grinding war that exhausts us both while France and Russia grow unchecked. Choose wisely.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, I am moving A SER to BUD to contest Italy - this is purely defensive and poses zero threat to you. F GRE moves to ION, A BUD supports A SER. I am not moving toward GAL, WAR, or RUM this turn. Italy at 6 centers is the dominant threat to the entire board - if you want to press me while I fight Italy, you hand Italy a free path to dominance. A ceasefire this season costs you nothing and keeps me as a buffer. I ask only that you hold F RUM and A UKR in place this turn. We can negotiate a longer arrangement once Italy is contained.'}]
