[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Our deal from last phase worked perfectly - I vacated GRE as promised, you took it uncontested. Now I need to discuss the current situation. Italy has occupied VIE and VEN, and has A VIE threatening my BUD. I have A BUD, A TRI, and F ION. I propose we coordinate against Italy - they are the dominant power with 6 centers and growing. I can push A TRI toward VEN or TYR while you consider pressure from the south. If Italy is not checked, they will dominate the board and threaten both of us. What are your intentions this fall? I want to ensure we don't work at cross-purposes."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, let's be direct: you hold VIE and VEN, I hold BUD and TRI. We are at a standoff. Continued conflict between us only benefits Russia and Turkey. I propose a formal ceasefire: I hold A TRI and A BUD in place, you hold A VIE and A VEN in place. Neither of us attacks the other this phase. This gives us both time to address the real threats - France is at BER, Russia holds GAL and SEV, Turkey has 5 centers. I am willing to accept the current territorial situation as a starting point for negotiation if you commit to not advancing on BUD this turn. What do you say?"}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, the board has changed dramatically. Italy now holds VIE, VEN, TRI, TUN, NAP, ROM - six centers and growing. France holds MUN, BER, PAR, BRE, MAR, SPA, POR - seven centers. These two powers are the dominant threats to everyone. I hold only BUD, SER, and GRE (now lost to Turkey). I am not your primary threat - Italy is. I propose we stop wasting energy on each other. You hold GAL; I won't contest it. In return, I ask you not to push into RUM or BUD. Let's both focus on the real dangers. A coordinated approach against Italy's overextension would benefit us both."}]
