[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "I accept your proposal. F AEG will move to ION this season - away from your territory entirely. I want to rebuild trust after last fall's misstep. My focus is finishing Austria: A VIE moves to BUD, A TRI holds or supports. With Austria eliminated, we can establish a clean division - western Balkans mine, eastern Balkans and Black Sea yours. Russia is moving A GAL toward BUD and A SEV toward RUM, which threatens both of us. A coordinated ITA-TUR front against Russian expansion makes strategic sense once Austria is gone. Let's confirm: F AEG-ION, you hold GRE and push where you see fit. No aggression between us."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, I must be direct: A GAL moving to BUD conflicts with my A VIE-BUD move - we will bounce each other and Austria survives. This benefits neither of us. I propose instead: A GAL supports my A VIE-BUD, ensuring the move succeeds and Austria is eliminated cleanly. BUD falls to me, and I acknowledge your sphere extends through RUM and the Black Sea region. Turkey is indeed a growing concern - my F AEG is moving to ION this season to reposition, but I am watching Turkish expansion carefully. Support my A VIE-BUD and we both benefit from Austria's elimination without wasting moves on a bounce."}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, your offer is noted but I cannot halt my advance - the strategic logic demands I secure BUD this season. However, I offer you this: direct F NAP against Turkey in ION or EAS rather than wasting it on ROM. Attacking my home centers only accelerates your elimination and gains you nothing. If you cooperate and move F NAP away from Italian territory, I will consider your remaining units as a potential buffer force rather than a target for immediate elimination. The choice is yours - die fighting me pointlessly, or redirect your fleet against Turkey and buy yourself time.'}]
